The paper presents a deep learning approach for a problem in the domain of high energy physics, specifically for vertex reconstruction of neutrino-nucleus interaction events. This involves combining energy and timing data collected in the MINERvA detector to perform classification and regression tasks. Given the focus on deep learning and the use of data from a detector, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the use of regression analysis and the domain-specific nature of the problem suggest that cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) may also be relevant sub-categories.
